description:
PHP driver performance issues with a disconnected secondary

Ref: https://groups.google.com/d/topic/mongodb-user/EjsLDj4JBIA/discussion

The driver used was the master branch from here https://github.com/mongodb/mongo-php-driver, phpinfo shows as 1.4.0dev, the latest commit was: 65d607d1570cbe75956ace990636907e337c904d.

The server version was 2.4.1

To reproduce:
Configure a replica set of two members and an arbiter.  One of the set members needs to be disconnect-able from the network (i.e. connection timeout, not closed socket).  I've been using a VirtualBox machine, and disconnecting the vnic.

In my test, .103:27018 is the primary, .110:27017 the secondary, and .103:27019 an arbiter.

Run mongostat against the primary, run the rather trivial save loop test below, and note the mongostat results.  
Disconnect the secondary, and note the changed mongostat results.

{code}
<?php
// Setup MongoLog
function show($a, $b, $message) { echo date('H:i:s '), $message, "\n"; }
MongoLog::setModule( MongoLog::ALL );
MongoLog::setLevel( MongoLog::ALL );
MongoLog::setCallback( 'show' );

$con = new
MongoClient('mongodb://192.168.1.103:27018,192.168.1.110:27017/?replicaSet=rs0');

while (true) {
    $con->test->test->save(array('foo' => uniqid()));
    usleep(100000);  // Reduce MongoLog volumes to manageable levels
}
?>
{code}

Observed behaviour:
Mongostat throughput drops to 0, if not indefinitely than for the 5 minutes I've waited.  Also the PHP test appears to hang, certainly no more log entries are generated.
2013-04-10-mongolog.txt and 2013-04-10-mongostat.txt provide the outputs, the secondary was disconnected approx 08:49:38

Expected behaviour:
Ideally a secondary failure shouldn't impact a connection to the primary at all.  But an exception or other handleable error would be acceptable.



Additionally, stopping and restarting the test (with the secondary still disconnected) resulted in generally normal performance, except that every 5-6 seconds throughput drops off sharply for 1-2 seconds, which seems to correlate with multiple "discover_topology:" entries in the MongoLog output. 
2013-04-10-mongolog-2.txt and 2013-04-10-mongostat-2.txt provide the outputs for this.

Expected behaviour:
The PHP driver should be able to handle a disconnected secondary without significant performance degradation.

When connecting directly to a replica set member, it is not possible to do any reads, I assume because - as it seems and some discussions hint - the driver never sets the slaveOk flag for standalone connections, no matter what I do.

When I enable logging, the driver says:
[Tue Apr 23 16:13:59 2013] [warn] [client A.B.C.D] mod_fcgid: stderr: PHP Notice:  REPLSET INFO: - connection: type: STANDALONE, socket: 8, ping: 0, hash: [...]
Thus, it uses a standalone connection, as expected.


E.g. this fails:
$mongo = new MongoClient("mongodb://${user}:${pass}@secondary");
$db = $mongo->__get("foo");
$coll = $db->__get("bar");
$count = $coll->count();

$count contains:
Array ( [note] => from execCommand [ok] => 0 [errmsg] => not master )

I can add "/?slaveOk=true" to the connection string, add setSlaveOkay(true) and setReadPreference(MongoClient::RP_SECONDARY) to MongoClient/MongoDB/MongoCollection, nothing helps (I tried pretty much all permutations).


I know how the readPreferences work and I am aware that they are the standard answer to the problem of reading from secondaries, but since I want to read from a *specific* secondary, they're useless. Maybe I could abuse tags for this, but that would be way more cumbersome.

In 1.2.x, I can do the following, and it works as expected:

$mongo = new Mongo("mongodb://${user}:${pass}@secondary");
$mongo->setSlaveOkay(true);
$db = $mongo->__get("foo");
$coll = $db->__get("bar");
$count = $coll->count();

But this exact code does not work in 1.3.x, probably because Mongo is just a wrapper around MongoClient in 1.3.x and thus did not keep the 1.2.x behaviour.

{code}
<?php

$mongo = new MongoClient('mongodb://localhost:27017/test');
$db = $mongo->test;
$item = array('test' => null);
$db->tests->save($item);

$item = $db->tests->findOne(array('_id' => $item['_id']));
var_dump($item['test']); // null
var_dump(isset($item['test'])); // false, wtf?
{code}

When attempting to perform a batch insert with the continueOnError flag set to TRUE, the batch insert fails to insert any documents when an invalid document is present in the array. The expected result is to insert the valid documents and skip the invalid document.
<code>
$docs = array(
			array('test' => 'hello'),
			array('' => 'zero length')
			array('test2' => 'hello'),

		);

		try{
			$this->collection->batchInsert($docs, array('continueOnError' => TRUE));
		} catch(Exception $e){
			echo $e->getMessage() . "\n";

		}
</code>

In this scenario, the batch insert throws the following exception: "zero-length keys are not allowed, did you use $ with double quotes?" and 0 documents are inserted.

